    "medgen_uid": "4297",
    "disease_name": "DiGeorge syndrome (DGS)",
    "concept_id": "C0012236",
    "disease_type": "Disease or Syndrome",
    "definition": "Individuals with 22q11.2 deletion syndrome (22q11.2DS) can present with a wide range of features that are highly variable, even within families. The major clinical manifestations of 22q11.2DS include congenital heart disease, particularly conotruncal malformations (ventricular septal defect, tetralogy of Fallot, interrupted aortic arch, and truncus arteriosus), palatal abnormalities (velopharyngeal incompetence, submucosal cleft palate, bifid uvula, and cleft palate), immune deficiency, characteristic facial features, and learning difficulties. Hearing loss can be sensorineural and/or conductive. Laryngotracheoesophageal, gastrointestinal, ophthalmologic, central nervous system, skeletal, and genitourinary anomalies also occur. Psychiatric illness and autoimmune disorders are more common in individuals with 22q11.2DS.",
    "synonyms": [
      "Catch22",
      "THIRD AND FOURTH PHARYNGEAL POUCH SYNDROME"
    ],
